    "rationale": "This reaction shows the decarbonylation of a simple aliphatic aldehyde, heptanal, to its corresponding alkane, hexane, using Wilkinson's catalyst. This is a classic textbook example of the Tsuji-Wilkinson decarbonylation, clearly demonstrating the conversion of an aldehyde functional group (-CHO) to a hydrogen atom (-H) with the loss of carbon monoxide. The substrate is a simple, acyclic, saturated chain, which is ideal for a canonical representation.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The use of a simple, long-chain aliphatic aldehyde avoids motifs common in other named reactions. It specifically avoids aromatic aldehydes (which could overlap with reactions involving arenes), alpha,beta-unsaturated aldehydes (related to conjugate additions), and acyl halides (which have their own distinct reactivity). This focuses the query squarely on the decarbonylation of a simple aldehyde, which is the core transformation of this reaction family."
